<h2>Section B: Attempt any eight questions.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Differentiate between primary data and secondary data. What are the sources of secondary data?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Primary data and secondary data are two types of data used in research and analysis, and they differ in terms of their sources, collection methods, and uses:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Primary Data:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Definition:</strong> Primary data is data that is collected directly from original sources for a specific research purpose. It is data that researchers gather firsthand for a particular study or investigation.</li>
<li><strong>Collection Method:</strong> Primary data is collected through methods such as surveys, interviews, observations, experiments, and direct measurements. Researchers design and conduct these data collection activities themselves.</li>
<li><strong>Freshness:</strong> Primary data is typically current and specific to the research question at hand.</li>
<li><strong>Control:</strong> Researchers have control over the collection process and can tailor it to their specific research needs.</li>
<li><strong>Examples:</strong> Responses from a survey conducted for a research project, measurements taken during a laboratory experiment, or observations made during ethnographic fieldwork.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Secondary Data:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Definition:</strong> Secondary data refers to data that has already been collected and compiled by someone else for a purpose other than the current research. It involves using existing data sources to analyze, interpret, or draw conclusions for a different research objective.</li>
<li><strong>Collection Method:</strong> Secondary data is collected by organizations, government agencies, research institutions, or individuals for purposes other than the researcher&#8217;s current project.</li>
<li><strong>Freshness:</strong> Secondary data may be historical or less current compared to primary data, as it was collected for a different reason and at a different time.</li>
<li><strong>Control:</strong> Researchers have limited control over the data collection process because they did not collect the data themselves.</li>
<li><strong>Examples:</strong> Census data, financial reports, academic journals, market research reports, historical documents, and publicly available datasets.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Sources of Secondary Data:</strong> Secondary data can be obtained from various sources, including:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Government Sources:</strong> Government agencies often collect and publish data on various topics, such as demographics, economics, health, and education. Examples include the U.S. Census Bureau, the World Health Organization (WHO), and national statistical offices.</li>
<li><strong>Academic Publications:</strong> Peer-reviewed journals, conference proceedings, and academic publications contain research findings, data, and statistics that can be used as secondary sources.</li>
<li><strong>Commercial Sources:</strong> Market research firms, business intelligence companies, and industry reports provide data on markets, consumer behavior, and industry trends.</li>
<li><strong>Nonprofit Organizations:</strong> Nonprofits, think tanks, and research organizations conduct studies and compile data on various social, economic, and environmental issues.</li>
<li><strong>Corporate Reports:</strong> Publicly traded companies release annual reports, financial statements, and other corporate documents that contain data on their financial performance, operations, and market insights.</li>
<li><strong>Libraries and Archives:</strong> Libraries, archives, and historical repositories house a wealth of primary and secondary sources, including books, manuscripts, newspapers, and government records.</li>
<li><strong>Online Databases:</strong> There are numerous online databases and data repositories that offer access to a wide range of secondary data, such as government data portals, academic databases, and data-sharing platforms.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>What is sampling? Define simple random sampling and stratified random sampling with some relevant examples.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><div class="group w-full text-token-text-primary border-b border-black/10 gizmo:border-0 dark:border-gray-900/50 gizmo:dark:border-0 bg-gray-50 gizmo:bg-transparent dark:bg-[#444654] gizmo:dark:bg-transparent" data-testid="conversation-turn-5">
<div class="p-4 justify-center text-base md:gap-6 md:py-6 m-auto">
<div class="flex flex-1 gap-4 text-base mx-auto md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-[38rem] xl:max-w-3xl }">
<div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]">
<div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3 max-w-full">
<div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-3 overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">
<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light">
<p><strong>Sampling</strong> is a fundamental technique in statistics and research methodology that involves selecting a subset of individuals or items from a larger population to study and draw conclusions about the entire population. Sampling is commonly used because it is often impractical or too expensive to collect data from an entire population. Instead, researchers use a sample that is representative of the population to make inferences.</p>
<p><strong>1. Simple Random Sampling:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Definition:</strong> Simple random sampling is a method in which each individual or item in the population has an equal chance of being selected for the sample. It involves randomly selecting individuals without any specific criteria or categories.</li>
<li><strong>Example:</strong> Suppose you want to conduct a survey to determine the average income of households in a city with a population of 10,000. To perform simple random sampling, you could assign a unique number to each household, and then use a random number generator to select 500 households from the list. This ensures that every household has an equal probability of being chosen.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>2. Stratified Random Sampling:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Definition:</strong> Stratified random sampling is a method in which the population is divided into distinct subgroups or strata based on certain characteristics (e.g., age, gender, income level), and then a random sample is taken from each subgroup. This ensures that each stratum is represented in the final sample, making it useful for studying specific subgroups.</li>
<li><strong>Example:</strong> Imagine you want to assess the educational performance of students in a large school with 2,000 students. You decide to use stratified random sampling by first categorizing the students into three strata: freshmen, sophomores, and juniors. Then, you randomly select 50 students from each stratum to create your sample. This approach ensures that you have a representative sample from each grade level.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Comparison:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Simple Random Sampling</strong> is suitable when the population is relatively homogenous, and there are no specific subgroups or characteristics of interest. It is a straightforward method but may not efficiently capture specific subpopulations.</li>
<li><strong>Stratified Random Sampling</strong>, on the other hand, is useful when there are distinct subgroups within the population that you want to study separately or when you want to ensure proportional representation of certain characteristics. It can provide more precise estimates for each stratum but requires knowledge of the population&#8217;s characteristics.</li>
</ul>
<p>Both sampling methods aim to reduce bias and ensure the sample accurately represents the population, but the choice between them depends on the research objectives and the characteristics of the population being studied.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>What aspect of summary measures of data can be explained by the measures of skewness? Kelvin Hota is the national sales manager for National Text Books. He has a sales staff of 10 who visit college professors all over the United States. Each Sunday morning he requires his sales staffs to send him a report. Listed below are the number of visits last week.</p>
<p>25, 6, 10, 13, 15, 2, 18, 5, 20, 30</p>
<p>Compute the five number summary.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Skewness is a measure of the asymmetry or departure from symmetry in a dataset. It helps us understand the shape of the data distribution. Skewness can be either positive (right-skewed) or negative (left-skewed), or it can be close to zero (approximately symmetric).</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>If skewness is <strong>positive (right-skewed)</strong>, it means that the right tail (larger values) of the distribution is longer or fatter than the left tail. This indicates that there are some high outliers in the data, and the majority of the data points are concentrated on the left side.</li>
<li>If skewness is <strong>negative (left-skewed)</strong>, it means that the left tail (smaller values) of the distribution is longer or fatter than the right tail. This suggests that there are some low outliers in the data, and most data points are concentrated on the right side.</li>
<li>If skewness is <strong>close to zero</strong>, it implies that the data distribution is approximately symmetric.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-25101" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/SmartSelect_20230922_163550_CamScanner.jpg" alt="" width="903" height="1137"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the requisites for good average? From the following distribution of marks 200 students of a college:</p>
<div class="table_wrapper"><table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Marks</td>
<td>30-40</td>
<td>40-50</td>
<td>50-60</td>
<td>60-70</td>
<td>70-80</td>
<td>80-90</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>No. of students</td>
<td>14</td>
<td>50</td>
<td>60</td>
<td>45</td>
<td>20</td>
<td>11</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Compute:</p>
<p>i. The minimum marks obtained by top 10% students.</p>
<p>ii. modal marks.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In statistics, an &#8220;average&#8221; is a measure of central tendency that summarizes a dataset by providing a single representative value. To ensure that an average is meaningful and useful in statistical analysis, certain requisites or criteria should be considered:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Representativeness:</strong> A good average should accurately represent the central or typical value of the dataset. It should provide a value that is not unduly influenced by extreme outliers or skewed data points.</li>
<li><strong>Additivity:</strong> The average should be additive, meaning that if you calculate the average of subgroups or segments of the data and then combine them, the overall average should be consistent with the original dataset&#8217;s average. This property is important for aggregating data.</li>
<li><strong>Ease of Interpretation:</strong> The average should be easily understood and interpreted by the audience or users of the data. It should convey a clear sense of the dataset&#8217;s central tendency without requiring complex explanations.</li>
<li><strong>Appropriateness to Data Type:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Arithmetic Mean:</strong> This is the most commonly used average and is suitable for interval and ratio data. It is the sum of all values divided by the number of values (n). It has the properties of additivity and is scale-dependent.</li>
<li><strong>Median:</strong> The median is suitable for ordinal, interval, and ratio data. It represents the middle value when the data is sorted. It is robust against outliers and skewed distributions.</li>
<li><strong>Mode:</strong> The mode is suitable for nominal and ordinal data. It represents the most frequent value(s) in a dataset.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Robustness:</strong> A good average should be robust against outliers or extreme values that can distort the interpretation of central tendency. The median and mode are often preferred when dealing with skewed or non-normally distributed data.</li>
<li><strong>Alignment with Research Objectives:</strong> The choice of average should align with the research question or objectives. Depending on the goals of the analysis, one type of average may be more appropriate than another.</li>
<li><strong>Scale Independence:</strong> The average should not be influenced by the choice of measurement units. It should give the same result regardless of whether the data is expressed in different units (e.g., pounds or kilograms).</li>
<li><strong>Statistical Properties:</strong> Some averages have specific statistical properties. For example, the arithmetic mean minimizes the sum of squared deviations from the mean (least squares), which is important in various statistical techniques.</li>
<li><strong>Context Sensitivity:</strong> Consider the context of the data and the research problem. Sometimes, multiple averages may need to be calculated and compared to provide a more comprehensive understanding of the dataset.</li>
<li><strong>Availability and Quality of Data:</strong> The choice of average should take into account the availability and quality of data. In some cases, you may need to use the average that can be calculated based on the data you have.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
